<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0076 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1018EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-BRF--YouthBurned     02-16 0179</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Youth Burned,0182</SECOND><HEAD>Hair Spray Can Explodes</HEAD><DATELINE>GREEN COVE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An 11-year-old boy was incritical condition today with severe burns suffered when a can ofhair spray he had ignited exploded in a fireball, authorities said.   Shane William Ziegler had first- and second-degree burns on hisface and neck and burns on his arm, chest and legs, said Clay Countysheriff's Lt. Tim Martin.   Shane, his 10-year-old brother and 14-year-old neighbor, AlanWorkman, used matches to ignite the vapor from two cans of hairspray in the front yard of the Ziegler home Tuesday night, Martinsaid.   ``He bent down and kind of squatted and I started to walk off,then I heard it go off,'' Workman said. ``I turned around and all Icould see was a red ball over the yard. It was about a 6-foot flamefrom where he was standing.''   With his shirt and pants on fire, Shane ran into Workman's houseand jumped into a bathtub to extinguish the flames. He was flown toShriners Burn Insitute in Cincinnati.</TEXT></DOC>